A 'bee-car' to prevent collisions
In development of the technologies for preventing accidents, Nissan was inspired by nature and particularly by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that imitates the flight of bees and can prevent accidents.
This is the Biomimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, the first step to project technologies for the prevention of collision.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Centre of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this little robot in collaboration with the Centre for Scientific Research and Technology of the University of Tokyo in Japan.
The BR23C is an expansion of the Security Shield of the four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is aimed at improving the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles produced by the company.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval personal space that is very similar to the Nissan Security Shield.
The most important element is the bee's compound eyes, which can see all directions with an extra 300 degree angle, allowing the insect to fly with no interruption inside its personal space.
Then, to recreate these visual features, engineers developed what they defined as a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism detects obstacles within 2 meters and a radius up to 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to the microprocessor on board that immediately prevents the collision.
The little robot imitates the bee's movement and changes direction immediately by turning the wheel at a right or wider angle to prevent the collision.
The most evident difference with any existing system is its evasive action which results in totally instinctive action.
If it were not so, the robot would not be able to react quickly to obstacles, explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Laboratory of Mobility and Head of the project.
The robot cannot shift upwards or downwards, or even diagonally. It can only move in two dimensions and in the direction its wheels turn.
The rotation function is a combination of the acceleration and deceleration functions to allow the little robot to prevent collisions.
This device only needs to process new information every few seconds, and act from this data.
It does not require any information or to use the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers. For this reason it can go without interruption supplied by a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we are not talking about gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step towards developing new technologies for the prevention of collisions, a technology Nissan hopes to be introduced in cars as standard feature within ten years.
The robot uses Lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion typology.
The potential application of this technology could be the integration of this technology with the GPS satellite navigator to bring the driver to a specific destination, avoiding obstacles along the path.
