Fortis bank partially nationalized by Benelux governments
Both the Benelux States are going to help Fortis, the Belgian-Dutch bank - which is the first European financial institution in trouble due to the follow-up effect of the American lending crisis - by a partial state buyout.
The end of this week, the Belgian, Luxembourg and the Netherlands governments took up this issue at the highest level, involving the President of the European Central Bank and the Competition Commissioner of the European Commission.
Within the Euro zone, Fortis is the first bank hit by the international financial crisis approaching in waves in the last 12 months. Thus, from a certain perspective, the decisions made may be considered precedent.
The decision was made on Sunday night, each government will take a 49 percent stake in Fortis banks in its respective countries.
The bank will certainly sell some of its stake, especially the insurance activities, acquired from the Netherlands ABN Amro last year.
shares started to drop last week, then in the second part of the week signs of a serious crisis appeared at the company.
