Fox In Henhouse
The American life and health insurance companies often refuse to sell insurance to some citizens, due to drug purchase data.
Data protection experts are afraid that the data market becomes uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection programme that requires the permission of the person concerned to use the drug prescription data.
It should be independent, otherwise the fox will be guarding the hen-house.
Insurance companies decide on the insurance fee and the amount to be paid in case of damage based on the health condition of the applying customer, and if they consider it too risky, they do not provide insurance.
The applying customers used to be sent to have a medical examination, and the contract was completed based on the results of the screening.
Dick developed a much cheaper method ten years ago: on the basis of the customer's identification number the type of drugs purchased by the customer in the last 18 months can be easily detected, thus the programme can draw the consequences of the illnesses the applicant suffers as well as their health.
Examples of regularly buying large doses of cholesterol-lowering drugs practically indicate that the customer has untreatably high blood cholesterol level, which would immediately cause the person to be placed in a higher risk category.
The programme has many versions in trade, some of them even define the risk factor, thus the insurance company has no other to do but paperwork.
The advantages of some drugs are that they can be used for several purposes, such as some medical formulas are used to treat migraine, heat waves or even depression.
The latter one is a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, while the other two are not.
There are specific companies involved in obtaining and processing data, and they ask patient permission to acquire the necessary information from the pharmacies.
The workers are already obliged to do so, though previous failures have not been penalized.
Some companies process even laboratory examinations and connect them to drug consumption data. This way they can provide more accurate information on the patient's health condition.
More and more companies gain access to the data and, alongside, control of its use becomes more difficult.
There is a specific act on health care data protection but its scope includes only health care providers and insurance companies.
The bill on providing inspection power for the authorities over companies dealing with data provision has been sent to the Congress.
Dick Richard realizes that it is not enough, and that is why he has further developed his programme, which now restricts data transfer without the express consent of the person concerned.
The other question is that the applicant cannot really refuse consent, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude contract with them.
So hens, at a certain degree, will continue to depend on the benevolence of the fox.
